any relevant information that can help clarify the details and provide the user with what they need. Let’s see what I can find!\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_jWsVEpsK2ey1jx1H4mpcqswY|fc_09467bfd90a6e5210169951b65ed3c8194bc41997754046dde","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -RIn \"sleep-box\\|dieline\\|nightpremium\\|organicline\\|minimal\" -n . | head -n 50","workdir":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director"},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"grep -RIn \\\"sleep-box\\\\|dieline\\\\|nightpremium\\\\|organicline\\\\|minimal\\\" -n . | head -n 50\",\"workdir\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ObiO4r421YvzGslS9Y77QNrH|fc_09467bfd90a6e5210169951b65ed508194866181d7fb2570fa","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find . -type f \\( -name \"*sleep*box*dieline*.svg\" -o -name \"*dieline*.svg\" -o -name \"*v1*minimal*.svg\" -o -name \"*v2*organicline*.svg\" -o -name \"*v3*nightpremium*.svg\" \\) -maxdepth 6","workdir":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director"},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"find . -type f \\\\( -name \\\"*sleep*box*dieline*.svg\\\" -o -name \\\"*dieline*.svg\\\" -o -name \\\"*v1*minimal*.svg\\\" -o -name \\\"*v2*organicline*.svg\\\" -o -name \\\"*v3*nightpremium*.svg\\\" \\\\) -maxdepth 6\",\"workdir\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_4DV4nIjto3EIw0sgwYBdk7Q5|fc_09467bfd90a6e5210169951b65ed5881949c442a7d1c8792d9","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -1 references | head","workdir":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director"},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"ls -1 references | head\",\"workdir\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_DYqw2ctxaiQoC8iapIPvRMj8|fc_09467bfd90a6e5210169951b65ed6081948668d7713cdab230","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/CREATIVE_LOOP.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director/CREATIVE_LOOP.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":833,"output":281,"cacheRead":5888,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7002,"cost":{"input":0.00145775,"output":0.003934,"cacheRead":0.0010304,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00642215}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771379552031}}
{"type":"message","id":"10175c8a","parentId":"57a0e3d8","timestamp":"2026-02-18T01:52:38.510Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_jWsVEpsK2ey1jx1H4mpcqswY|fc_09467bfd90a6e5210169951b65ed3c8194bc41997754046dde","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:12:**Controlled complexity:** minimal surfaces, high-resolution decisions.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:23:6. **Material Truth:** If the surface is minimal, are typography/materials/lighting actually excellent?\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:96:- Feel: elegant distance, minimal provocation.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:152:- Composition: calm, straightforward, minimal staging.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:191:- One short thesis line at top; minimal labels.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:4:Purple is fashion/art editorial as a cool, minimal provocation: sparse layouts, bold casting, and a refusal to over-explain. It’s a magazine that understands *distance*—letting images and names exist with a kind of deadpan confidence. Purple’s best lesson is that luxury can be weird without being loud; it can be conceptual while still being sensual. The risk is empty cool; when it works, it’s because the curation is strong and the restraint is disciplined. For Zara, Purple is about minimal packaging with sharp cultural choices.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:19:- **High-end product launches**: minimal comms with confident silence.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:24:- minimal type + strong curation\n./references/influences/dossiers/susan-sontag.md:24:- cool minimal typography\n./references/influences/dossiers/dieter-rams.md:4:Rams is the patron saint of disciplined reduction: not minimalism as a look, but as an ethical stance against clutter and dishonesty. His “Ten Principles for Good Design” came out of real industrial constraints at Braun—mass production, durability, and user trust. The enduring value is that his rules are operational: useful, understandable, unobtrusive, thorough, environmentally considerate. Rams also shows that restraint needs craft; otherwise it’s just emptiness. For Zara, Rams is a hard standard: if you can’t explain why an element exists, it doesn’t.\n./references/influences/dossiers/dieter-rams.md:23:- white/grey industrial minimal\n./references/influences/dossiers/scott-stowell.md:4:Scott Stowell’s Open is a masterclass in being smart without being slick. The studio’s work often feels like a clever sentence: a simple form with a twist that reveals the concept. Stowell also models a sustainable creative practice—small team, wide range, consistently high taste—without chasing agency bloat. The brand value is “playful intelligence”: design that invites a second look and rewards attention. For Zara, Stowell is a reminder that restraint doesn’t mean humorless; you can be minimal *and* mischievous.\n./references/influences/dossiers/scott-stowell.md:24:- minimal with one weird detail\n./references/influences/dossiers/apc.md:4:A.P.C. is understatement as identity: clean French basics, sharp fit, and an anti-hype tone that reads confident rather than quiet. The brand’s power is consistency—materials, silhouettes, and a restrained palette that turns “normal” into a signature. A.P.C. also nails collaborations by keeping the core language intact; collabs feel like extensions, not costume changes. The denim programs show how to make process and patina part of the product story without turning it into heritage theater. For Zara, A.P.C. is the lesson that a brand can be minimal and still have a point of view if the standards are high.\n./references/influences/dossiers/apc.md:22:- French minimal\n./references/influences/dossiers/naoto-fukasawa.md:19:- **Modern fintech apps**: one-path flows (sign up, transfer, invest) with minimal branching.\n./references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md:4:Auralee is “premium basics” done the hard way: obsessive fabric development, calm silhouettes, and colors that look like light on stone. The brand’s minimalism isn’t generic—it’s textile-first, where the surface (hand, drape, density) is the differentiator. Auralee also demonstrates Japanese restraint without austerity: warmth, softness, and lived-in elegance. It’s a reminder that luxury can be quiet if the materials are unmistakable up close. For Zara, Auralee is the lesson that minimal brands win on *sensory proof*.\n./references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md:18:- **COS**: accessible minimalism when elevated by fabric choices.\n./references/influences/dossiers/yves-saint-laurent.md:4:YSL is sharp elegance with an edge: tailoring, black-as-architecture, and a brand that made modern sexuality legible through clothes. The house built iconic codes (Le Smoking, tuxedo language, sharp shoulders) that are instantly readable and endlessly remixable. Under later eras (including Saint Laurent branding), the lesson becomes how to modernize without losing codes—tight typography, stark imagery, and a controlled palette. YSL also proves that “minimal” can be aggressive, not soft. For Zara, YSL is the template for iconic code discipline: pick a few elements and make them unstoppable.\n./references/influences/dossiers/kenya-hara.md:4:Kenya Hara is minimalism with *meaning*: not “less” as an aesthetic, but emptiness as a receptive field for perception and culture. As Muji’s art director and a prolific writer (notably *Designing Design*), he argues that design should sharpen awareness—materials, rituals, and everyday life—rather than shout. His work leverages whiteness, paper, and silence to create a high-resolution feeling of calm. Importantly, Hara is not generic modernism; he’s tuned to Japanese notions of void, interval, and implicit communication. For Zara, Hara is the playbook for restraint that still feels rich—where absence becomes a brand asset.\n./references/influences/dossiers/032c.md:22:- Berlin minimal editorial\n./references/influences/dossiers/james-turrell.md:4:Turrell makes light behave like architecture: not illumination of objects, but light as the object. His work trains perception—color fields, skyspaces, and immersive volumes that make you doubt the boundary between seeing and knowing. The craft is engineering-level (space, apertures, controlled luminance) delivered as spiritual calm. For brands, Turrell is the ultimate lesson in *experience design*: the medium is the user’s attention. For Zara, Turrell is how you make “minimal” feel unforgettable—by manipulating light, time, and perception rather than adding graphics.\n./references/influences/dossiers/peter-saville.md:4:Saville is art direction as cultural engineering: he made record sleeves feel like modern art with mass distribution. With Factory Records (Joy Division, New Order), he fused appropriation, typography, and conceptual distance into icons that still feel contemporary. His work teaches that *mystery* can be a system—controlled ambiguity, selective information, and impeccable proportion. He’s also a study in taste as curation: the best move is often choosing the right reference and framing it cleanly. For Zara, Saville is about tension: minimal surfaces with emotional charge underneath.\n./references/influences/dossiers/peter-saville.md:22:- record sleeve minimalism\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:4:Mies is structural clarity turned into atmosphere: the building is an exact system, and the experience is calm authority. “Less is more” is often misread as visual emptiness; for Mies it’s about reducing to essential structure, proportion, and material truth. The drama comes from precision—steel, glass, stone—and the choreography of grids and planes. He also teaches that minimalism is expensive: it forces quality because there’s nowhere to hide. For Zara, Mies is the guide for spatial/brand environments: make the structure obvious, the details perfect, and let the space do the persuasion.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:14:8. If you go minimal, raise the quality bar across everything.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:19:- **Packaging**: rigid structure + one premium material + minimal print.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:24:- serene minimal interiors\n./references/influences/dossiers/bauhaus.md:4:Bauhaus is not “minimalism”; it’s a program to unify art, craft, and industry into a modern language that can be produced and taught. The school treated design as a total system—typography, furniture, architecture, performance—built from geometry, materials, and function. Its output is both formal (grids, primary shapes) and institutional (pedagogy, workshops, standards). The danger is cosplay: Bauhaus aesthetics pasted onto products without the functional/industrial logic. For Zara, Bauhaus is the system-building ancestor: make a coherent language that can live across objects, spaces, and media.\n./references/influences/dossiers/bauhaus.md:28:- Wassily Chair by Marcel Breuer — Tubular steel and minimalist planes.\n./references/influences/WORLD.md:13:6. **Material Truth:** In minimal work, is the craft (type, light, material) actually excellent?\n./references/influences/WORLD.md:39:- **DON'T:** Use minimalism as a mask for a lack of ideas or poor craft.\n./references/influences/YES.md:36:- **Mies van der Rohe** — structure-first calm authority. Steal: minimal surfaces demand perfect detail; choreograph space like UX.  \n./references/influences/YES.md:62:- **Auralee** — texture-forward minimal luxury. Steal: fabric proof + atmospheric color; minimal silhouettes to showcase drape.  \n./references/influences/YES.md:82:- **Purple Magazine** — minimal provocation. Steal: negative space as status; selection as the brand; deadpan cool.  \n./references/influences/NOTES.md:9:The taste target isn’t minimalism—it’s **controlled complexity**: a tight system that can host weirdness.\n./references/influences/NOTES.md:51:If the surface is minimal, are materials/typography/lighting actually excellent?\n./references/influences/NOTES.md:52:- If no: minimalism will expose you (Mies/Rams).\n./references/influences/ROWAN_SYNTHESIS.md:56:7. **Attention design** (Turrell/Mies): Engineer perception—light, pace, silence, transitions—so minimal feels rich.\n./references/influences/ROWAN_SYNTHESIS.md:85:6. **Material Truth Rule:** If the surface is minimal, execution quality must be demonstrably high (type, spacing, light, materials). Otherwise add structure, not ornament.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Vignelli_Massimo.md:18:- Not motion-first; if animated, keep motion grid-locked and minimal (slides/fades), with clear hierarchy at every frame.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Vignelli_Massimo.md:33:- “Vignelli minimalism” as aesthetic poverty; the rigor is in the system and execution.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Glaser_Milton.md:18:- Not motion-first; if adapted to motion, animate like a poster: big shapes, clear holds, minimal transitions.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Norman_Don.md:34:- UI clutter as “discoverability”; good signifiers can still be minimal.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Rand_Paul.md:18:- Not motion-first; if animated, keep it logo-simple: minimal transforms, clear holds, and no decorative physics.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Hara_Kenya.md:18:- Relevant only if pursuing “quiet motion”: long holds, minimal transforms, and transitions that preserve calm (fade, slow reveal, no bounce).\n./references/designers/dossiers/Spiekermann_Erik.md:18:- Not motion-first; when type moves, keep it readable at speed: bigger sizes, longer holds, minimal words, predictable transitions.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Bierut_Michael.md:21:- Let typographic voice do brand work (authoritative, civic, playful) with minimal styling.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Tschichold_Jan.md:35:- Confusing minimalism with lack of hierarchy; you still need strong emphasis.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Maeda_John.md:34:- “Simplicity” as aesthetic minimalism; the goal is reduced cognitive load, not empty screens."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":84,"aggregated":"./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:12:**Controlled complexity:** minimal surfaces, high-resolution decisions.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:23:6. **Material Truth:** If the surface is minimal, are typography/materials/lighting actually excellent?\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:96:- Feel: elegant distance, minimal provocation.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:152:- Composition: calm, straightforward, minimal staging.\n./references/influences/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md:191:- One short thesis line at top; minimal labels.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:4:Purple is fashion/art editorial as a cool, minimal provocation: sparse layouts, bold casting, and a refusal to over-explain. It’s a magazine that understands *distance*—letting images and names exist with a kind of deadpan confidence. Purple’s best lesson is that luxury can be weird without being loud; it can be conceptual while still being sensual. The risk is empty cool; when it works, it’s because the curation is strong and the restraint is disciplined. For Zara, Purple is about minimal packaging with sharp cultural choices.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:19:- **High-end product launches**: minimal comms with confident silence.\n./references/influences/dossiers/purple-magazine.md:24:- minimal type + strong curation\n./references/influences/dossiers/susan-sontag.md:24:- cool minimal typography\n./references/influences/dossiers/dieter-rams.md:4:Rams is the patron saint of disciplined reduction: not minimalism as a look, but as an ethical stance against clutter and dishonesty. His “Ten Principles for Good Design” came out of real industrial constraints at Braun—mass production, durability, and user trust. The enduring value is that his rules are operational: useful, understandable, unobtrusive, thorough, environmentally considerate. Rams also shows that restraint needs craft; otherwise it’s just emptiness. For Zara, Rams is a hard standard: if you can’t explain why an element exists, it doesn’t.\n./references/influences/dossiers/dieter-rams.md:23:- white/grey industrial minimal\n./references/influences/dossiers/scott-stowell.md:4:Scott Stowell’s Open is a masterclass in being smart without being slick. The studio’s work often feels like a clever sentence: a simple form with a twist that reveals the concept. Stowell also models a sustainable creative practice—small team, wide range, consistently high taste—without chasing agency bloat. The brand value is “playful intelligence”: design that invites a second look and rewards attention. For Zara, Stowell is a reminder that restraint doesn’t mean humorless; you can be minimal *and* mischievous.\n./references/influences/dossiers/scott-stowell.md:24:- minimal with one weird detail\n./references/influences/dossiers/apc.md:4:A.P.C. is understatement as identity: clean French basics, sharp fit, and an anti-hype tone that reads confident rather than quiet. The brand’s power is consistency—materials, silhouettes, and a restrained palette that turns “normal” into a signature. A.P.C. also nails collaborations by keeping the core language intact; collabs feel like extensions, not costume changes. The denim programs show how to make process and patina part of the product story without turning it into heritage theater. For Zara, A.P.C. is the lesson that a brand can be minimal and still have a point of view if the standards are high.\n./references/influences/dossiers/apc.md:22:- French minimal\n./references/influences/dossiers/naoto-fukasawa.md:19:- **Modern fintech apps**: one-path flows (sign up, transfer, invest) with minimal branching.\n./references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md:4:Auralee is “premium basics” done the hard way: obsessive fabric development, calm silhouettes, and colors that look like light on stone. The brand’s minimalism isn’t generic—it’s textile-first, where the surface (hand, drape, density) is the differentiator. Auralee also demonstrates Japanese restraint without austerity: warmth, softness, and lived-in elegance. It’s a reminder that luxury can be quiet if the materials are unmistakable up close. For Zara, Auralee is the lesson that minimal brands win on *sensory proof*.\n./references/influences/dossiers/auralee.md:18:- **COS**: accessible minimalism when elevated by fabric choices.\n./references/influences/dossiers/yves-saint-laurent.md:4:YSL is sharp elegance with an edge: tailoring, black-as-architecture, and a brand that made modern sexuality legible through clothes. The house built iconic codes (Le Smoking, tuxedo language, sharp shoulders) that are instantly readable and endlessly remixable. Under later eras (including Saint Laurent branding), the lesson becomes how to modernize without losing codes—tight typography, stark imagery, and a controlled palette. YSL also proves that “minimal” can be aggressive, not soft. For Zara, YSL is the template for iconic code discipline: pick a few elements and make them unstoppable.\n./references/influences/dossiers/kenya-hara.md:4:Kenya Hara is minimalism with *meaning*: not “less” as an aesthetic, but emptiness as a receptive field for perception and culture. As Muji’s art director and a prolific writer (notably *Designing Design*), he argues that design should sharpen awareness—materials, rituals, and everyday life—rather than shout. His work leverages whiteness, paper, and silence to create a high-resolution feeling of calm. Importantly, Hara is not generic modernism; he’s tuned to Japanese notions of void, interval, and implicit communication. For Zara, Hara is the playbook for restraint that still feels rich—where absence becomes a brand asset.\n./references/influences/dossiers/032c.md:22:- Berlin minimal editorial\n./references/influences/dossiers/james-turrell.md:4:Turrell makes light behave like architecture: not illumination of objects, but light as the object. His work trains perception—color fields, skyspaces, and immersive volumes that make you doubt the boundary between seeing and knowing. The craft is engineering-level (space, apertures, controlled luminance) delivered as spiritual calm. For brands, Turrell is the ultimate lesson in *experience design*: the medium is the user’s attention. For Zara, Turrell is how you make “minimal” feel unforgettable—by manipulating light, time, and perception rather than adding graphics.\n./references/influences/dossiers/peter-saville.md:4:Saville is art direction as cultural engineering: he made record sleeves feel like modern art with mass distribution. With Factory Records (Joy Division, New Order), he fused appropriation, typography, and conceptual distance into icons that still feel contemporary. His work teaches that *mystery* can be a system—controlled ambiguity, selective information, and impeccable proportion. He’s also a study in taste as curation: the best move is often choosing the right reference and framing it cleanly. For Zara, Saville is about tension: minimal surfaces with emotional charge underneath.\n./references/influences/dossiers/peter-saville.md:22:- record sleeve minimalism\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:4:Mies is structural clarity turned into atmosphere: the building is an exact system, and the experience is calm authority. “Less is more” is often misread as visual emptiness; for Mies it’s about reducing to essential structure, proportion, and material truth. The drama comes from precision—steel, glass, stone—and the choreography of grids and planes. He also teaches that minimalism is expensive: it forces quality because there’s nowhere to hide. For Zara, Mies is the guide for spatial/brand environments: make the structure obvious, the details perfect, and let the space do the persuasion.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:14:8. If you go minimal, raise the quality bar across everything.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:19:- **Packaging**: rigid structure + one premium material + minimal print.\n./references/influences/dossiers/mies-van-der-rohe.md:24:- serene minimal interiors\n./references/influences/dossiers/bauhaus.md:4:Bauhaus is not “minimalism”; it’s a program to unify art, craft, and industry into a modern language that can be produced and taught. The school treated design as a total system—typography, furniture, architecture, performance—built from geometry, materials, and function. Its output is both formal (grids, primary shapes) and institutional (pedagogy, workshops, standards). The danger is cosplay: Bauhaus aesthetics pasted onto products without the functional/industrial logic. For Zara, Bauhaus is the system-building ancestor: make a coherent language that can live across objects, spaces, and media.\n./references/influences/dossiers/bauhaus.md:28:- Wassily Chair by Marcel Breuer — Tubular steel and minimalist planes.\n./references/influences/WORLD.md:13:6. **Material Truth:** In minimal work, is the craft (type, light, material) actually excellent?\n./references/influences/WORLD.md:39:- **DON'T:** Use minimalism as a mask for a lack of ideas or poor craft.\n./references/influences/YES.md:36:- **Mies van der Rohe** — structure-first calm authority. Steal: minimal surfaces demand perfect detail; choreograph space like UX.  \n./references/influences/YES.md:62:- **Auralee** — texture-forward minimal luxury. Steal: fabric proof + atmospheric color; minimal silhouettes to showcase drape.  \n./references/influences/YES.md:82:- **Purple Magazine** — minimal provocation. Steal: negative space as status; selection as the brand; deadpan cool.  \n./references/influences/NOTES.md:9:The taste target isn’t minimalism—it’s **controlled complexity**: a tight system that can host weirdness.\n./references/influences/NOTES.md:51:If the surface is minimal, are materials/typography/lighting actually excellent?\n./references/influences/NOTES.md:52:- If no: minimalism will expose you (Mies/Rams).\n./references/influences/ROWAN_SYNTHESIS.md:56:7. **Attention design** (Turrell/Mies): Engineer perception—light, pace, silence, transitions—so minimal feels rich.\n./references/influences/ROWAN_SYNTHESIS.md:85:6. **Material Truth Rule:** If the surface is minimal, execution quality must be demonstrably high (type, spacing, light, materials). Otherwise add structure, not ornament.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Vignelli_Massimo.md:18:- Not motion-first; if animated, keep motion grid-locked and minimal (slides/fades), with clear hierarchy at every frame.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Vignelli_Massimo.md:33:- “Vignelli minimalism” as aesthetic poverty; the rigor is in the system and execution.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Glaser_Milton.md:18:- Not motion-first; if adapted to motion, animate like a poster: big shapes, clear holds, minimal transitions.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Norman_Don.md:34:- UI clutter as “discoverability”; good signifiers can still be minimal.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Rand_Paul.md:18:- Not motion-first; if animated, keep it logo-simple: minimal transforms, clear holds, and no decorative physics.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Hara_Kenya.md:18:- Relevant only if pursuing “quiet motion”: long holds, minimal transforms, and transitions that preserve calm (fade, slow reveal, no bounce).\n./references/designers/dossiers/Spiekermann_Erik.md:18:- Not motion-first; when type moves, keep it readable at speed: bigger sizes, longer holds, minimal words, predictable transitions.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Bierut_Michael.md:21:- Let typographic voice do brand work (authoritative, civic, playful) with minimal styling.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Tschichold_Jan.md:35:- Confusing minimalism with lack of hierarchy; you still need strong emphasis.\n./references/designers/dossiers/Maeda_John.md:34:- “Simplicity” as aesthetic minimalism; the goal is reduced cognitive load, not empty screens.","cwd":"/Users/calbotsman/.openclaw/workspace-director"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1771379558506}}
